populo plebique: originally populu-s- meant the patricians aud the clientes only; while plebs was used of the subjugated popula- tions of conquered towns imported to Rome, who had no share in political rights and privileges. The phrase ‘populus et plebs‚’ however, was kept to designate the whole body of Roman citizens long after the two classes had ceased to be politically distinct.
